The IMF needs more Lagarde.
Davos—Lagarde once said she remains open to serving another five years as the head of the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
She should be reappointed.
The IMF has never had a better leadership than her, and the IMF Board should give her an opportunity to complete the work she started.
Lagarde took office in July 2011, inheriting an institution beset by crisis.
The 2008 global financial meltdown and its economic aftershocks left the credibility of Western-led multilateral lending institutions and the free market "Washington Consensus" in tatters.
Lagarde's leadership helped the IMF re-establish its reputation.
Many eyes have turned to her personal qualities —— and that is as it should be.
She has confessed, demonstrated strength, shown warmth, and moved people.
Foreign officials who met her (often in delicate settings) have all expressed that she dares to speak out on difficult realities, while also being a sensitive listener.
For a leader of an institution that must negotiate terms rather than dictate everything, these are important qualities.
Lagarde told Europeans that their banks needed to be restructured, otherwise they would have to build a firewall to prevent financial contagion. Honest words are hard to hear, but Europeans still went ahead and did it.
Similarly, she has loudly called for IMF support to be provided to some countries - such as Greece, Pakistan, Tunisia, and Ukraine - which is crucial for global stability.
There are countless examples.
The IMF is not known for innovation and is not typically passionate.
Lagarde began to change this.
Under her leadership, the IMF has gained a more humane face, which is rare for an institution that typically prescribes bitter medicine.
Similarly, helping to manage the Middle East refugee crisis was not within the IMF's original mandate.
Under her leadership, the IMF adjusted its plans, enabling the Jordanian government to allocate more funds to help those displaced by the conflicts in Syria and Iraq, many of whom are residing in refugee camps within Jordan's borders.
Similarly, in 2014, when the Ebola outbreak hit West Africa, Lagarde led the IMF in using its available resources to provide debt relief to countries affected by the crisis, enabling them to increase the salaries of doctors and nurses - a first for the IMF in using its own capital.
In addition, Lagarde recognizes that the world is currently facing three major challenges, and she has taken action against them.
First, she has been a strong advocate for bringing more women into the workforce, and she herself serves as a role model for women in leadership positions.
In various countries from Saudi Arabia to Japan, she urges leaders to stop squandering such vast human resources – and to tap into economic potential in the process.
Secondly, under her leadership, the IMF has also addressed the broader issue of income inequality.
It is not just a matter of basic fairness.
IMF research emphasizes a direct link between narrowing income disparities and boosting economic growth.
While the IMF is not the first to demonstrate this, its position makes this issue more pronounced and pressing.
Christine Lagarde has been a personal advocate for this issue, which is a key factor in its heightened urgency.
Thirdly, Lagarde has played a crucial role in helping the world understand the full implications of technological change – some of which will have a devastating impact.
For instance, automation will continue to boost efficiency and lower costs in manufacturing, but it also implies that the number of jobs generated by economic growth will be fewer than before.
This new reality's political, economic, and social implications deserve our recognition and serious study.
Lagarde made the IMF the core of this work.
Critics say it's time for developing countries to take the helm at the IMF.
After all, Lagarde is one of the 11 consecutive Europeans to hold this position, and it is challenging for Europe to have such a privilege in today's world.
Some critics argue that the austerity measures supported by the IMF in Greece have not been entirely effective, indicating that she has become disconnected from the general public.
Some critics point out that she faces allegations related to a financial scandal in France, which would distract her from her work at the IMF.
After her predecessor Dominique Strauss-Kahn became embroiled in a scandal, critics argued that the IMF could not afford to be distracted by similar events once again.
Let's break down these criticisms.
The IMF, as well as the World Bank, should welcome leaders from outside Europe and the United States.
The goal is to end the Western privilege by making the leadership selection process based on merit rather than politics.
Lagarde is the best candidate for IMF president, and emerging powers such as the BRICS nations (Brazil, Russia, India, and China) have not yet coalesced behind an alternative candidate.
Having an IMF president from Europe may also have been a factor in the IMF's decision last year to include the Chinese currency in the basket of currencies used to determine its Special Drawing Rights (SDR) value.
In addition, Lagarde demonstrated remarkable political flexibility in ultimately convincing the US Congress's Republican and Democratic parties to approve IMF governance reforms, which not only strengthened the IMF's arsenal to combat financial crises but also more accurately reflected the dynamics of a rapidly changing global economy.
For example, the BRICS nations have now entered the top ten shareholder list of the IMF.
In the case of Greece, Lagarde made some blunt comments last year, which some people found rather unbecoming.
But she is not the one responsible for bringing economic hardship to the Greeks; during her tenure at the IMF, she has fully demonstrated that in the history of the IMF, no president has done as much as she has to lead the IMF's efforts to alleviate the suffering of people in times of crisis.
Finally, the charges against Lagarde were opposed by the French prosecutor, and Lagarde was at most only marginally implicated.
The world urgently needs a leader who is committed to making the world a safer and more prosperous place.
Lagarde has proven herself to be such a leader, committed to ensuring that the IMF adapts to the 21st century.
She deserves a chance to see things through.
